@generic{Rye2020,
   abstract = {This paper applies the concept of a grid-forming control structure through the implementation of a virtual synchronous machine (VSM) to a conventional 250-kW utility-scale photovoltaic (PV) inverter. VSM is a recently-developed control scheme which offers an alternative grid-synchronization method to the conventional grid-tracking control which utilizes a phase-locked-loop (PLL). Synchronous machines inherently synchronize to the grid and largely partake in the stabilization of the grid frequency during power system dynamics. The purpose of this paper is primarily to present the derivation of the terminal d-q ac impedance of the small-signal model of the inverter and grid-forming control scheme as well as to assess the stability of this control topology under unity power factor, constant reactive power, and reactive power droop control modes. Additionally, a comparison between the small-signal stability of the grid-tracking and grid-forming control will be made.},
