@report{,
   abstract = {As steam turbine generator units increase in rating, their inertia constants tend to decrease and their reactance constants to increase, thus aggravating the power system transient stability problem. There is also a tendency for the complete unit to take longer to restart and reload when unscheduled discon-nection from the system takes place. Counter measures are needed and may be available within the power plant. A study of these measures was made by the authors acting as a Working Group of NewEngland's NEPLAN Planning Committee's System Design Task Force. The paper presents the Working Group's findings as widely supported by the major utilities in New Eng-land. INTRODUCTION a. Physical Limitations of Fault Clearing Equipment In recent years, with the interconnection of many large power systems, the trend has been toward higher voltage transmission lines and larger generating units. These interconnected power systems have proven to be both reliable and economical. Several problems have been encountered, however, from this method of operation, leading to increased diffi-cu lty in maintaining system stability. The large generating plants, in most cases, are located a considerable distance from load centers formanyeconomic and political reasons. The power must then be transmitted to the load centers via high voltage transmission lines and today, power companies are finding it increasingly diffi-cu It to obtain right-of-ways for these overhead high voltage lines. Many lines are delayed years after planned in-service date and some plans are even abandoned. These problems can have an adverse effect on the stability of the system. Another factor affecting stabi lity is the relatively low inertia of new generating units. During system short circuits , they tend to speed up faster than most older and smaller units and, therefore, are less stable. The accelerating power of a turbine-generator unit is equated to the mechanical power input tothe turbine minusthe